    subtitle: '— Repressed Lyricism in Documentary "Only Dawn Smiles"',
    excerpt: 'An analysis of documentary filmmaking as bearing witness through the metaphor of a parrot.',
    date: 'October 18, 2023',
    readTime: '5 min read',
    tags: ['Film', 'Documentary'],
    customImages: ['/images/poetry-parrots-dawn.jpg'],
    imageIds: [132, 133, 134],
    content: [
      "In my view, Chen Jiaping's documentary Paradise, How Far? is grounded in a parrot-like mode of lyricism—being present, watching, recording, and reproducing.",
      "On October 30, 2022, director Gu Tao hosted a screening of Paradise, How Far?",
      "A parrot is an animal that spends its entire life mimicking human speech, yet can never truly express emotion through language. Its body becomes an objective vessel, storing the sounds it hears in an inner chamber of memory. While the people in a household move steadily toward tomorrow, the parrot, often inadvertently, begins to recite voices from yesterday—voices long forgotten. Within four walls, echoes of the past linger, reverberating until the parrot's death.",
      "In my view, Paradise, How Far? is built upon precisely this kind of parrot-like lyricism: presence, observation, recording, reenactment. Chen Jiaping, though a direct participant in all that unfolds, presents himself only through the silence of a bystander. Upon this carefully constructed silence arise other sounds: the grief-stricken singing at poet Hu Xudong's funeral; the choked speech at his friend Kun Niao's wedding; his wife's relentless reproaches in a car at midnight; the anxious counsel of his aging father. Like all poets, Chen Jiaping longs for 'the stillness of the open wilderness,' yet he understands all too clearly that 'his life is not a life lived alone.' His life is the sum of the lives of those he loves. Within this helpless yet tender cacophony, he chooses to become an 'unfeeling' parrot—silently remembering an affectionate life. And yet, this does not prevent him, beyond the parrot's narration, from yearning for a voice that is truly his own: the poet's voice.",
      "At the beginning of the film, Chen Jiaping washes up in a bathroom. A broadcast commemorating the centenary of the founding of the Chinese Communist Party blends seamlessly with the sound of running water—an utterly mundane fusion, yet one that inevitably produces an inner dissonance. The broadcast serves as a conduit for an official, grand narrative, diffusing a set of words entirely detached from everyday life into its smallest details. Against this generational background noise, Chen Jiaping opens the tap, allowing the ordinary, flowing moments of life of poets born in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s to surface before the audience.",
      "Throughout the film, Chen Jiaping places himself deliberately low within the crowd. He admits that his interactions with poets such as Ma Yan (1979–2010) and Ma Hua (1972–2004) were not particularly close—merely sharing the same office air. Yet he preserves, intact in memory, that shared breath, carrying it across time to present it once more to the viewer. We are fortunate to see archival footage of Ma Yan speaking while alive. But this nested cinematography constantly reminds us that the poet's image has already been sealed into historical record. Even more poignant is the moment when the camera turns to poet Hu Xudong (1974–2021): the director draws us back into a first-person perspective, listening to a young 'Hu Zi' passionately analyzing Ma Yan's poetic structure in Chongqing dialect, as though he were still here before us, speaking to us directly.",
      "If mourning the dead is painful, then what is even more desolate is watching the dead mourn the dead from the vantage point of the future. At Ma Yan's funeral, Hu Xudong asked friends from all walks of life to write postcards—Ma Yan's favorite—for her. Yet in August 2021, Hu Xudong himself died suddenly from an epileptic seizure, and we found ourselves again at a funeral, singing him farewell: 'Weiming Lake is an ocean / Poets hide beneath its surface / Souls are all fish / Rising now and then to the light'",
      "Poets—though you have already journeyed to a more beautiful paradise, why do I still feel that you remain among us? Perhaps you are only hidden beneath the water's surface. Your undying poetry tethers your undying souls, surging again and again into our lives, into our hearts.",
      "On the other side of the screen, I could barely hold back my tears. Chen Jiaping, however, stood apart from the crowd, gazing at the camera in silence. To continue filming even during mourning should not be hastily interpreted as emotional detachment. Chen is pursuing a form of witnessing and participation imbued with historical weight. The cost is an objective lens that forever stands between him and what he sees. Such a commitment to remembrance and responsibility is, for an ordinary person immersed in grief, both heavy and cruel. Thus, beyond public mourning, he also seeks out narrow corners in which to retreat into private reflection and emotion. As the car disappears into a stormy night, his emotions surge quietly beneath the music.",
      "At the wedding of Kun Niao, a poet born in the 1980s, I saw him awkwardly encased in a suit. Half-jokingly, he commanded the audience: 'You must bless me—I have no choice.' Why must there be blessings? Why is there no choice? His speech did not celebrate a shared love, but reaffirmed the predicament of an individual. The absence of family weighed heavily on him; family, it seemed, were the roots of life, while friends were gifts gathered during the body's wandering. 'I'm already very satisfied—I've done everything I wanted to do,' he said. For many, a wedding signifies less the beginning of a new life than the ritualized end of an old one. He had once 'lived in this place in a way that was out of tune'—would marriage bring that dissonance to an end? As he stepped into this sacred space, the wind swept across his hair, covering one eye; the other reddened. The poet cried, without leaning toward the bride.",
      "Chen Jiaping once had an accident while filming as he drove. Later, his wife reproached him for filming, while he remained silent, eyes fixed on the camera. Between cinéma vérité and direct cinema, Chen chooses the former, acknowledging that in certain moments he amplifies the camera's presence, using its burden as a means to further dissect reality. In the scene of his wife's reproach, the camera's presence honestly reflects the power dynamics between husband and wife in that moment—he is always listening, always watching.",
      "City neon lights wash over Chen's face; fireworks burst overhead; from above, an empty lot appears—nearly desolate. Along an endless coastline, from below, a full moon rises—distant yet bright. Carrying all his memories, he returns to his 'cell,' only now without an 'iris' to carry him aloft.",
      "Yes—the parrot has died. The parrot that participated alongside Chen Jiaping throughout the film died in the middle of the night. But I believe that the poet Chen Jiaping still holds onto the ideal of the 'iris,' only buried deeper. In the black frames at the beginning and end of the film, the poet discards the parrot-like images of record. What remains is only his poetic monologue, spoken in his native accent. Poetry may be the only way, under the arrangements of our time, for us to arrive at 'a life of one's own.'",
      "I do not know what the parrot's death ultimately signifies for Chen Jiaping. I only see that as his wife and daughter weep, Chen once again takes out his phone. Perhaps he understands better than anyone that mourning is everywhere, permeating every night of life. We will all eventually fall asleep in the dark of mourning, tears still wet—and when you wake—dawn is still smiling.",
      "October 15, 2022 | New York"
    ],
